{"title_page": "Hybrid bicycle", "text_new": "{{For|motorized-pedal hybrids|motorized bicycle}}\n'''Hybrid bicycles''' blend characteristics from more specialized [[racing bicycle|road bikes]], [[touring bike]]s and [[mountain bike]]s.<ref name = sheldonbrown1>{{cite web\n|title=Sheldon Brown's Bicycle Glossary \u2013 Hybrid Bicycle\n|url = http://sheldonbrown.com/gloss_ho-z.html#hybrid\n|quote = Hybrid bicycles, also known as \"cross\" or \"fitness\" bicycles, are a cross between a mountain bike and a touring bike. The best of them have the handlebars and control levers of a mountain bike, with the frame, gears, wheels and brakes of a touring bike\n|accessdate = 2008-11-07\n}}</ref> The resulting \"hybrid\" is a general-purpose bike that can tolerate a wide range of riding conditions and applications. Their stability, comfort and ease of use make them popular with novice cyclists, casual riders, commuters, and children.\n\nHybrid bikes can be called the [[Swiss Army knife|Swiss Army Knife]] of bicycles. Hybrid bikes harmonize the characteristics of road bikes, mountain bikes, and touring bikes. \n\nHybrids typically borrow the flat, straight handlebars and upright seating posture of a mountain bike, which many bicyclists find comfortable and intuitive. Hybrids also employ the lighter weight, thinner wheels and smooth tires of road bikes, allowing for greater speed and less exertion when riding on the road. Hybrid bikes often have places to mount racks and bags for transporting belongings, much like a touring bike.\n\nHybrid bikes have spawned numerous sub-categories satisfying diverse ridership. They are classified by their design priorities, such as those optimized for comfort or fitness &mdash; and those offered as city, cross or commuter bikes.<ref name=\"Richard\">\n{{cite book\n|last=Ballantine\n|first=Richard\n|authorlink=Richard Ballantine\n|title=Richard's 21st Century Bicycle Book\n|year=2001\n|publisher=Overlook Press\n|location=New York\n|isbn=1-58567-112-6\n|pages=[https://archive.org/details/richards21stcent00ball/page/32 32\u201339]\n|url-access=registration\n|url=https://archive.org/details/richards21stcent00ball/page/32\n}}</ref>\n\nHybrid bikes provide many benefits<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ourbikeguide.com/hybrid-bikes/|title=Hybrid Bikes|last=|first=|date=2020-04-08|website=Our Bike Guide|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>. They are highly comfortable, affordable, and are suited for all terrains. They can even help you to improve your health.\n\n<br />\n\n==History==\nFrom the early 20th century until after World War II, the [[Roadster (bicycle)|utility roadster]] constituted most adult bicycles sold in the United Kingdom and in many parts of the British Empire. In Britain, the roadster declined noticeably in popularity during the early 1970s, as a boom in recreational cycling caused manufacturers to concentrate on lightweight (23-30&nbsp;lb.), affordable [[Derailleur gears|derailleur]] sport bikes, actually slightly-modified versions of the racing bicycle of the era. In the 1980s, U.K. cyclists began to shift from road-only bicycles to all-terrain models such as the [[mountain bike]]. The mountain bike's sturdy frame and load-carrying ability gave it additional versatility as a utility bike, usurping the role previously filled by the roadster. By 1990, the roadster was almost dead; while annual U.K. bicycle sales reached an all-time record of 2.8 million, almost all of them were mountain and road/sport models. A different situation, however, was occurring in most Asian countries: roadsters are still widely made and used in countries such as China, India, Thailand, Vietnam and others as well in parts of north-western Europe. {{Citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\n==Trekking bike==\n[[File:AERO-RS1-Trekking.jpg|thumb|Lightweight trekking bike]]\nA trekking bike is a hybrid with all the accessories necessary for [[bicycle touring]]{{spaced ndash}}mudguards, pannier rack, lights etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctc.org.uk/DesktopDefault.aspx?TabID=3508|title=Trekking bike|publisher=[[Cyclists' Touring Club]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheldonbrown.com/gloss_tp-z.html#trekking|title=Sheldon Brown's Bicycle Glossary \u2013 Trekking Bicycle|author=Sheldon Brown}}</ref>\n\n==Cross bike==\nCross bikes use a road [[bicycle frame]] similar to a [[racing bicycle|racing]] or sport/[[touring bicycle]], and are normally equipped with nearly flat handlebars to provide a more upright riding position than a racing or sport/touring bike.<ref name=\"Richard\"/> As a hybrid bike intended for general recreational and utility use, the ''cross bike'' differs from the [[cyclo-cross bicycle]], which is a racing bicycle purposely designed to compete in the sport of [[cyclo-cross]] competition. Cross bikes are fitted with 700c (ISO 622) [[bicycle wheel|wheels]] using somewhat wider semi-treaded tires ({{convert|1.125|\u2013|1.25|in|mm|abbr=on|disp=or}}) <!-- ({{convert|1.125|\u2013|1.25|in|mm|abbr=out|disp=or}}) --> than those fitted to most racing or sport/touring models.<ref name = sheldonbrown1/>\nThe additional tire width and tread is intended to give the cross bike hybrid some ability to deal with rough or littered surfaces that might be encountered on paved or unpaved bike trails, such as gravel, leaves, hard-packed sand, and shallow mud. Most cross bikes are biased towards moderate off-pavement use and light weight, and as such are not normally fitted with fenders, lights, or carrier racks. The larger 700c wheels are a little faster on paved surfaces and can give an advantage for longer trips or for touring purposes.<ref name=\"Richard\"   />\n\n==Commuter bike==\nThe commuter bike is a hybrid designed specifically for commuting over short or long distances. It typically features derailleur gearing, 700c wheels with fairly light {{convert|1+1/8|in|mm|adj=on}} tires, a carrier rack, full fenders, and a frame with suitable mounting points for attachment of various load-carrying baskets or panniers. It sometimes, though not always, has an enclosed chainguard to allow a rider to pedal the bike in long pants without entangling them in the chain. A well-equipped commuter bike typically features front and rear lights for use in the early morning or late evening hours encountered at the start or end of a business day.<ref name=\"Richard\"/>\n\n==City bike==\n[[File:Hybrid-bicycle-1.jpg|thumb|The 2005 [[Giant Manufacturing|Giant]] Innova is an example of a typical 700c hybrid city [[bicycle]].]]\nSimilar to the commuter bike, the city bike is more optimized for urban commuting.<ref name=\"Richard\"/> Unlike the [[European city bike]], it has mountain bike heritage, gearing, and strong yet lightweight frame construction.<ref name=\"Richard\"/><ref>Howells, Bob, and Lehrer, John, ''A City Bike Sampler'', Outside Magazine (March 1992), Vol. 17, pp. 88-91</ref><ref>Mellion, Morris B., ''Sports Medicine Secrets'', Elsevier Health Sciences, 3rd ed. (2003), {{ISBN|1-56053-548-2}}, {{ISBN|978-1-56053-548-5}}, p. 552</ref><ref>Museum of Mountain Bike Art & Technology [http://www.mombat.org/Trek.htm Article]</ref> It usually features mountain bike-sized [[Bicycle wheel#26 inch / ISO 559 mm|26-inch (ISO 559)]] wheels, a more upright seating position, and \"middleweight\" {{convert|1.5|\u2013|1.95|in|mm|adj=on}} heavy belted tires designed to withstand road hazards commonly found in the city, such as broken glass.<ref name=\"Richard\"/><ref name=\"Howells\">Howells, pp. 88\u201391</ref> Using a sturdy welded [[41xx steel|chromoly]] or [[aluminium]] frame derived from the mountain bike, the city bike is more capable at handling urban hazards such as deep potholes, drainage grates, and jumps off city curbs.<ref name=\"Richard\"/><ref name=\"Howells\"/> City bikes are designed to have reasonably quick, yet solid and predictable handling, and are normally fitted with full fenders for use in all weather conditions.<ref name=\"Richard\"/> A few city bikes may have enclosed chainguards, others may have suspension forks, similar to mountain bikes. City bikes may also come with front and rear lighting systems for use at night or in bad weather.<ref name=\"Richard\"/>\n\n==Comfort bike==\n[[File:Giant_Sedona.jpg|thumb|A [[Giant_Bicycles|Giant]] brand Sedona comfort bike on the [[Pinellas_Trail|Pinellas Trail]] in [[Dunedin,_Florida|Dunedin]], [[Florida]]]].\n[[File:Trek Navigator 200 comfort bike.jpg|thumb|[[Trek Bicycle Corporation|Trek]] Navigator 200 comfort bike]]\n{{See also|Roadster (bicycle)}}\nAnother subclass of the hybrid category is the comfort bike. Comfort bikes are essentially modern versions of the old ''[[Roadster (bicycle)|roadster]]'' and ''sports roadster'' bicycle,<ref name=\"Richard\"/> though modern comfort bikes are often equipped with [[derailleur gears]] rather than [[hub gear]]s. They typically have a modified mountain bike frame with a tall head tube to provide an upright riding position, [[Bicycle wheel#26 inch / ISO 559 mm|26-inch (ISO 559)]] or 28-inch (ISO 622) wheels, and {{convert|1.75|or|1.95|in|mm|adj=on}} \"middleweight\" smooth or semi-slick tires. Comfort bikes typically incorporate such features as front suspension [[Bicycle fork|forks]], [[Bicycle suspension|seat post suspension]] with wide plush saddles, and drop-center, angled [[Bicycle handlebar#Upright or North Road|North Road-style handlebars]] designed for easy reach while riding in an upright position.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Outline of cycling]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Hybrid bikes}}\n* {{Britannica|909551|Hybrid bicycle (vehicle)}}\n{{Human-powered vehicles}}\n\n[[Category:Cycle types]]\n[[Category:Road cycles]]\n[[Category:Hybrid vehicles|B]]\n\n[[de:Trekkingrad]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|motorized-pedal hybrids|motorized bicycle}}\n'''Hybrid bicycles''' blend characteristics from more specialized [[racing bicycle|road bikes]], [[touring bike]]s and [[mountain bike]]s.<ref name = sheldonbrown1>{{cite web\n|title=Sheldon Brown's Bicycle Glossary \u2013 Hybrid Bicycle\n|url = http://sheldonbrown.com/gloss_ho-z.html#hybrid\n|quote = Hybrid bicycles, also known as \"cross\" or \"fitness\" bicycles, are a cross between a mountain bike and a touring bike. The best of them have the handlebars and control levers of a mountain bike, with the frame, gears, wheels and brakes of a touring bike\n|accessdate = 2008-11-07\n}}</ref> The resulting \"hybrid\" is a general-purpose bike that can tolerate a wide range of riding conditions and applications. Their stability, comfort and ease of use make them popular with novice cyclists, casual riders, commuters, and children.\n\nHybrids typically borrow the flat, straight handlebars and upright seating posture of a mountain bike, which many bicyclists find comfortable and intuitive. Hybrids also employ the lighter weight, thinner wheels and smooth tires of road bikes, allowing for greater speed and less exertion when riding on the road. Hybrid bikes often have places to mount racks and bags for transporting belongings, much like a touring bike.\n\nHybrid bikes have spawned numerous sub-categories satisfying diverse ridership. They are classified by their design priorities, such as those optimized for comfort or fitness &mdash; and those offered as city, cross or commuter bikes.<ref name=\"Richard\">\n{{cite book\n|last=Ballantine\n|first=Richard\n|authorlink=Richard Ballantine\n|title=Richard's 21st Century Bicycle Book\n|year=2001\n|publisher=Overlook Press\n|location=New York\n|isbn=1-58567-112-6\n|pages=[https://archive.org/details/richards21stcent00ball/page/32 32\u201339]\n|url-access=registration\n|url=https://archive.org/details/richards21stcent00ball/page/32\n}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nFrom the early 20th century until after World War II, the [[Roadster (bicycle)|utility roadster]] constituted most adult bicycles sold in the United Kingdom and in many parts of the British Empire. In Britain, the roadster declined noticeably in popularity during the early 1970s, as a boom in recreational cycling caused manufacturers to concentrate on lightweight (23-30&nbsp;lb.), affordable [[Derailleur gears|derailleur]] sport bikes, actually slightly-modified versions of the racing bicycle of the era. In the 1980s, U.K. cyclists began to shift from road-only bicycles to all-terrain models such as the [[mountain bike]]. The mountain bike's sturdy frame and load-carrying ability gave it additional versatility as a utility bike, usurping the role previously filled by the roadster. By 1990, the roadster was almost dead; while annual U.K. bicycle sales reached an all-time record of 2.8 million, almost all of them were mountain and road/sport models. A different situation, however, was occurring in most Asian countries: roadsters are still widely made and used in countries such as China, India, Thailand, Vietnam and others as well in parts of north-western Europe. {{Citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\n==Trekking bike==\n[[File:AERO-RS1-Trekking.jpg|thumb|Lightweight trekking bike]]\nA trekking bike is a hybrid with all the accessories necessary for [[bicycle touring]]{{spaced ndash}}mudguards, pannier rack, lights etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctc.org.uk/DesktopDefault.aspx?TabID=3508|title=Trekking bike|publisher=[[Cyclists' Touring Club]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheldonbrown.com/gloss_tp-z.html#trekking|title=Sheldon Brown's Bicycle Glossary \u2013 Trekking Bicycle|author=Sheldon Brown}}</ref>\n\n==Cross bike==\nCross bikes use a road [[bicycle frame]] similar to a [[racing bicycle|racing]] or sport/[[touring bicycle]], and are normally equipped with nearly flat handlebars to provide a more upright riding position than a racing or sport/touring bike.<ref name=\"Richard\"/> As a hybrid bike intended for general recreational and utility use, the ''cross bike'' differs from the [[cyclo-cross bicycle]], which is a racing bicycle purposely designed to compete in the sport of [[cyclo-cross]] competition. Cross bikes are fitted with 700c (ISO 622) [[bicycle wheel|wheels]] using somewhat wider semi-treaded tires ({{convert|1.125|\u2013|1.25|in|mm|abbr=on|disp=or}}) <!-- ({{convert|1.125|\u2013|1.25|in|mm|abbr=out|disp=or}}) --> than those fitted to most racing or sport/touring models.<ref name = sheldonbrown1/>\nThe additional tire width and tread is intended to give the cross bike hybrid some ability to deal with rough or littered surfaces that might be encountered on paved or unpaved bike trails, such as gravel, leaves, hard-packed sand, and shallow mud. Most cross bikes are biased towards moderate off-pavement use and light weight, and as such are not normally fitted with fenders, lights, or carrier racks. The larger 700c wheels are a little faster on paved surfaces and can give an advantage for longer trips or for touring purposes.<ref name=\"Richard\"   />\n\n==Commuter bike==\nThe commuter bike is a hybrid designed specifically for commuting over short or long distances. It typically features derailleur gearing, 700c wheels with fairly light {{convert|1+1/8|in|mm|adj=on}} tires, a carrier rack, full fenders, and a frame with suitable mounting points for attachment of various load-carrying baskets or panniers. It sometimes, though not always, has an enclosed chainguard to allow a rider to pedal the bike in long pants without entangling them in the chain. A well-equipped commuter bike typically features front and rear lights for use in the early morning or late evening hours encountered at the start or end of a business day.<ref name=\"Richard\"/>\n\n==City bike==\n[[File:Hybrid-bicycle-1.jpg|thumb|The 2005 [[Giant Manufacturing|Giant]] Innova is an example of a typical 700c hybrid city [[bicycle]].]]\nSimilar to the commuter bike, the city bike is more optimized for urban commuting.<ref name=\"Richard\"/> Unlike the [[European city bike]], it has mountain bike heritage, gearing, and strong yet lightweight frame construction.<ref name=\"Richard\"/><ref>Howells, Bob, and Lehrer, John, ''A City Bike Sampler'', Outside Magazine (March 1992), Vol. 17, pp. 88-91</ref><ref>Mellion, Morris B., ''Sports Medicine Secrets'', Elsevier Health Sciences, 3rd ed. (2003), {{ISBN|1-56053-548-2}}, {{ISBN|978-1-56053-548-5}}, p. 552</ref><ref>Museum of Mountain Bike Art & Technology [http://www.mombat.org/Trek.htm Article]</ref> It usually features mountain bike-sized [[Bicycle wheel#26 inch / ISO 559 mm|26-inch (ISO 559)]] wheels, a more upright seating position, and \"middleweight\" {{convert|1.5|\u2013|1.95|in|mm|adj=on}} heavy belted tires designed to withstand road hazards commonly found in the city, such as broken glass.<ref name=\"Richard\"/><ref name=\"Howells\">Howells, pp. 88\u201391</ref> Using a sturdy welded [[41xx steel|chromoly]] or [[aluminium]] frame derived from the mountain bike, the city bike is more capable at handling urban hazards such as deep potholes, drainage grates, and jumps off city curbs.<ref name=\"Richard\"/><ref name=\"Howells\"/> City bikes are designed to have reasonably quick, yet solid and predictable handling, and are normally fitted with full fenders for use in all weather conditions.<ref name=\"Richard\"/> A few city bikes may have enclosed chainguards, others may have suspension forks, similar to mountain bikes. City bikes may also come with front and rear lighting systems for use at night or in bad weather.<ref name=\"Richard\"/>\n\n==Comfort bike==\n[[File:Giant_Sedona.jpg|thumb|A [[Giant_Bicycles|Giant]] brand Sedona comfort bike on the [[Pinellas_Trail|Pinellas Trail]] in [[Dunedin,_Florida|Dunedin]], [[Florida]]]].\n[[File:Trek Navigator 200 comfort bike.jpg|thumb|[[Trek Bicycle Corporation|Trek]] Navigator 200 comfort bike]]\n{{See also|Roadster (bicycle)}}\nAnother subclass of the hybrid category is the comfort bike. Comfort bikes are essentially modern versions of the old ''[[Roadster (bicycle)|roadster]]'' and ''sports roadster'' bicycle,<ref name=\"Richard\"/> though modern comfort bikes are often equipped with [[derailleur gears]] rather than [[hub gear]]s. They typically have a modified mountain bike frame with a tall head tube to provide an upright riding position, [[Bicycle wheel#26 inch / ISO 559 mm|26-inch (ISO 559)]] or 28-inch (ISO 622) wheels, and {{convert|1.75|or|1.95|in|mm|adj=on}} \"middleweight\" smooth or semi-slick tires. Comfort bikes typically incorporate such features as front suspension [[Bicycle fork|forks]], [[Bicycle suspension|seat post suspension]] with wide plush saddles, and drop-center, angled [[Bicycle handlebar#Upright or North Road|North Road-style handlebars]] designed for easy reach while riding in an upright position.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Outline of cycling]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Hybrid bikes}}\n* {{Britannica|909551|Hybrid bicycle (vehicle)}}\n{{Human-powered vehicles}}\n\n[[Category:Cycle types]]\n[[Category:Road cycles]]\n[[Category:Hybrid vehicles|B]]\n\n[[de:Trekkingrad]]\n", "name_user": "Davidr39", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add some minor details that were missing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hybrid_bicycle"}
